%md
# Airbnb - New York's Analysis

**Author**: Jackson Antonio do Prado Lima
**E-mail**: japlima at inf dot ufpr dot br

Last updated: Apr 26th, 2017 (ver 1.0)
Spark: 2.1

## Abstract

Airbnb is an outstanding hosting service used worldwide and provides information to its users in a simple and efficient manner, although this information is limited only to listings of its products. In this work, an analysis is made taking into account if incidents and cultural organizations influence the prices practiced in Airbnb. Besides, the prediction of new prices is carried out that the user can come to inform taking into account information of the current listings. The price forecast has some advantages when advising the user: on the price practiced (is too large or small), the mode of advertisement, or even on the investment decisions of the market analysis. To help in this task, the present work performs an analysis using graphs, maps and different types of machine learning.

## Airbnb

The company was founded in August of 2008 and based in San Francisco, California. Airbnb is an online marketplace and hospitality service, enabling people to lease or rent short-term lodging including vacation rentals, apartment rentals, homestays, hostel beds, or hotel rooms. The company does not own any lodging; it is merely a broker and receives percentage service fees (commissions) from both guests and hosts in conjunction with every booking. It has over 3,000,000 lodging listings in 65,000 cities and 191 countries, and the host sets the cost of accommodation. Like all hospitality services, Airbnb is a form of collaborative consumption and sharing. Airbnb has two million rooms available - nearly three times more than that of the largest hotel chain in the world. Airbnb's customers can be broken down into two groups: guests and property hosts. 

## Experiment Description

### Research Questions

-Pergunta de Pesquisa
"Consigo simular a eleição de um candidato a vereador?"

- Começaremos prevendo o preço de listagem que esperamos que o usuário insira para um aluguel, com base nos atributos da listagem. Ser capaz de prever o preço tem várias aplicações: podemos aconselhar o cliente sobre o preço de uma unidade (talvez exibir um aviso se o número escolhido é muito grande ou pequeno), auxiliar na forma de anunciá-lo, ou informar a nossa própria análise do Mercado para decisões de investimento.
- Impact of proximity of (hotels, subways, attractions) on listing price
- Impact of the cultural organizations on listing price
- Impact of the incidents on listing price
- How can we use average value rating, average location rating, etc. in the data?

### Target Data

The investigation focused on four dataset collected in open data sites. These dataset are as follows: 1) Listings, a dataset that is a Airbnb snapshot of 02 April, 2017; 2) Incidents, contains all incidents from New York for the year 2016; 3) Cultural Organizations, contains all cultural organizations from New York; and 4) NYC Borough, contains informations about boundaries of boroughs (districts). Further information about these dataset is available in the table below. This table show the a additional information, the url to download, and the size of the files.

|#| Dataset | Description | Resource | Size | Download |
|-| ---- | ----- | -------- | ---- | -------- |
|1| Listings | Detailed listings data, including various attributes (features) of each listing such as number of bedrooms, bathrooms, location, etc. Date Compiled on **02 April, 2017** | listings.csv.gz | 153,7MB | [gz](http://data.insideairbnb.com/united-states/ny/new-york-city/2017-04-02/data/listings.csv.gz) |
|2| Incidents | This dataset includes all valid felony, misdemeanor, and violation crimes reported to the New York City Police Department (NYPD) for all complete quarters so far this year (2016). | NYPD_Complaint_Data_Current_YTD.csv | 124,2MB | [csv](https://data.cityofnewyork.us/Public-Safety/NYPD-Complaint-Data-Current-YTD/5uac-w243/data) |
|3| Cultural Organizations | Listing of all Cultural Organizations in the Department of Cultural Affairs directory | cultural_organizations.csv | 333,3kB | [csv](https://data.cityofnewyork.us/Recreation/DCLA-Cultural-Organizations/u35m-9t32) |
|4| NYC Borough | Polygon boundaries of boroughs (water areas excluded). | nyc_borough_boundaries.geojson | 400,5kB | [GeoJson](http://data.beta.nyc/dataset/nyc-borough-boundaries/resource/7c164faa-4458-4ff2-9ef0-09db00b509ef?view_id=8c05eff7-54d1-4359-8183-0e278e91b01a) |

### Settings

#### Clean up data

After download all data, it’s necessary to do a workaround to clean the listings raw data. In some columns, like description and name, the data is difficult to read. These columns contain break lines inside the text, text delimiters, besides other things that make a hard work to clean up and it prevents correct reading of the file. For this, it’s used R language to read the CSV, clean, organize and save in a new CSV.

paragraphs.title: R libraries
Workaround to clean data
paragraphs.text:
%r
dataset <- read.csv('data/NewYork/raw_data/listings.csv')

# remove "wrong" columns, just selecting the important columns to analysis
dataset <- dataset[,c("id","latitude","longitude","is_location_exact","host_id","host_name","host_response_time","host_response_rate","host_is_superhost","host_listings_count","host_total_listings_count","host_identity_verified","neighbourhood_cleansed","neighbourhood_group_cleansed","property_type","room_type","accommodates","bathrooms","bedrooms","beds","bed_type","price","weekly_price","monthly_price","security_deposit","cleaning_fee","guests_included","extra_people","minimum_nights","maximum_nights","availability_30","availability_60","availability_90","availability_365","number_of_reviews","review_scores_rating","review_scores_accuracy","review_scores_cleanliness","review_scores_checkin","review_scores_communication","review_scores_location","review_scores_value","reviews_per_month","instant_bookable","cancellation_policy","require_guest_profile_picture","require_guest_phone_verification","calculated_host_listings_count")]

# drop any entries that are obviously strange, such as listings with a value of 0 for bedrooms, beds, or price
dataset <- subset(dataset, bedrooms != 0 & beds != 0 & price != 0)

# special processing to remove a large number of NaN values
dataset <- mutate(dataset, 
                    reviews_per_month = as.numeric(ifelse(is.na(reviews_per_month),0,reviews_per_month)),
                    review_scores_value = ifelse(is.na(review_scores_value),0,review_scores_value),
                    review_scores_location = ifelse(is.na(review_scores_location),0,review_scores_location),
                    review_scores_communication = ifelse(is.na(review_scores_communication),0,review_scores_communication),
                    review_scores_checkin = ifelse(is.na(review_scores_checkin),0,review_scores_checkin),
                    review_scores_cleanliness = ifelse(is.na(review_scores_cleanliness),0,review_scores_cleanliness),
                    review_scores_accuracy = ifelse(is.na(review_scores_accuracy),0,review_scores_accuracy),
                    review_scores_rating = ifelse(is.na(review_scores_rating),0,review_scores_rating),
                    cleaning_fee = ifelse(is.na(cleaning_fee),0,cleaning_fee),
                    security_deposit = ifelse(is.na(security_deposit),0,security_deposit),
                    monthly_price = ifelse(is.na(monthly_price),0,monthly_price),
                    weekly_price = ifelse(is.na(weekly_price),0,weekly_price),
                    host_response_rate = ifelse(is.na(host_response_rate),0,host_response_rate)
                )
                
# convert the 'price' columns as price
dataset <- mutate(dataset,                 
                    price = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", price)), 
                    weekly_price = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", weekly_price)),
                    monthly_price = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", monthly_price)),
                    security_deposit = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", security_deposit)),
                    cleaning_fee = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", cleaning_fee)),
                    extra_people = as.numeric(gsub("[$,]", "", extra_people)))
                    
#rename columns
names(dataset)[names(dataset)=="neighbourhood_group_cleansed"] <- "district"
names(dataset)[names(dataset)=="neighbourhood_cleansed"] <- "neighbourhood"

write.csv2(dataset, file='data/NewYork/cleaned_data/listings.csv', row.names=FALSE)

%md

### Pyspark integration

Now we can import the necessary libraries for our project and read the files correctally.

Different ways were used to read the csv. This apporach was used to learn more about Apache Spark. The approaches used were:
- sqlContext with databricks (default)
- parquet (improve the read)
- pandas (easy way to create a new dataframe with new columns)

In this step, it was create a unique dataframe with the necessary informations. To help in the analsys, the Cultural Organizations and Incidents dataset receveid a score a they are like a column unique in the new dataframe. How we have 5 districts in New York, and to be easy, the Cultural Organizations and Incidents dataset were grouped and ranked in relation to the order (1-5), where 1 is the work and 5 the best. In this case, the datasets were ordered by the number in each district, `asc` for cultural organizations and `desc` for the incidents.

paragraphs.title: Read Data
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

cultural_organizations = sqlContext.read.format("com.databricks.spark.csv").options(header="true", delimiter=",", charset="ISO-8859-1", inferSchema="true").load("data/NewYork/cultural_organizations.csv")

nypdComplaintStreamRaw = sqlContext.read.format("com.databricks.spark.csv").options(header="true", delimiter=",", charset="ISO-8859-1", inferSchema="true").load("data/NewYork/NYPD_Complaint_Data_Current_YTD.csv")

airbnbDetailedStreamRaw = sqlContext.read.format("com.databricks.spark.csv").options(header="true", delimiter=";", charset="ISO-8859-1", inferSchema="true").load("data/NewYork/cleaned_data/listings.csv")
  
# Convert the dataset to a more efficent format to speed up our analysis
airbnbDetailedStreamRaw.write.mode("overwrite").format("parquet").save("data/NewYork/airbnb-detailed-stream")
nypdComplaintStreamRaw.write.mode("overwrite").format("parquet").save("data/NewYork/nypd-complaint-stream")
  
#Load the optimized data as a DataFrame
nypd_complaint = sqlContext.read.parquet("data/NewYork/nypd-complaint-stream")
airbnb = sqlContext.read.parquet("data/NewYork/airbnb-detailed-stream")

#Make the data available as a SQL table
cultural_organizations.registerTempTable("culturalorganizations")
nypd_complaint.registerTempTable("nypdcomplaint")
airbnb.registerTempTable("airbnb")

sfP = sqlContext.sql("""SELECT *, district cultural_organizations, district incidents FROM airbnb""").toPandas()

countCultural = cultural_organizations.select("borough").groupBy("borough").count() \
                    .selectExpr("borough as District", "cast(count as float) AS Number").orderBy("Number")
                    
countIncidents = nypd_complaint.select(func.initcap("BORO_NM").alias("BORO_NM")).select("BORO_NM").groupBy("BORO_NM") \
                    .count().selectExpr("BORO_NM as District", "cast(count as float) AS Number")\
                    .orderBy(func.desc("Number"))
                    
cultural = {}
incidentes = {}

for index, each in enumerate(countCultural.collect()):
     cultural[each[0]] = index

for index, each in enumerate(countIncidents.collect()):
     incidentes[each[0]] = index
     
# new values for cultural_organizations and nypd_complaint columns
sfP.replace({"cultural_organizations": cultural}, inplace=True)
sfP.replace({"incidents": incidentes}, inplace=True)

dfAll = spark.createDataFrame(sfP)
dfAll.registerTempTable("dfAll")

%md

## Analyzing the data

The objective of this step is to know the data and improve our understanding of the problem. The dataset contains 37043 rows, where each row represents a listing on the Airbnb and each column contains some information about them. Addictionally, ratings were created for the cultural and incident indexes, respectivally the columns: cultural_organizations and nypd_complaint (incidents). The columns are:

- **id**: listing id
- **latitude** and **longitude**: latitude and longitude of the listing
- **is_location_exact**: a boolean thats confirm the localization
- **host_id**: the host id
- **host_name**: the host name
- **host_response_time**: the host response time 
- **host_response_rate**: the host response rate 
- **host_is_superhost**: if the host is superhost
- **host_listings_count**: the host listings count
- **host_total_listings_count**: the host total listings count
- **host_identity_verified**: if the host was verified
- **neighbourhood**: the listings neibourhood
- **district**: the listings district
- **property_type**: These options are pretty straightforward. To avoid any confusion, Airbnb added a brief description of each property (home) type that appears when your mouse hovers over. Select the option that best describes your place. Keep in mind that the drop-down menu to the right expands your list of choices pretty significantly, including everything from loft, to castle, to tent.
- **room_type**: all listings are grouped into the following three room types: **Shared rooms**, **Private rooms**, **Entire homes/apartments**. 
    - **Shared rooms** are for when you'd like a comfy, communal experience, and don't mind sharing a space with others. When you book a shared room, you'll be sharing your bedroom and the entire space with other people. These rooms work best for the flexible traveler looking for new friends and a budget-friendly stay.
    - **Private rooms** are great for when you prefer a little privacy, but still value a local connection. When you book a private room, you'll have a bedroom to yourself, but will share some spaces with others. With a private room, you'll be able to wake up to greet your new friends in the kitchen and have the freedom to bid them adieu at bedtime.
    - **Entire homes/apartments** are best if you're seeking a home away from home with complete privacy and the freedom to cook breakfast in your pajamas. With an entire home/apartment, you'll have the whole space to yourself. You can be your own host, make your own dinner, and remember to treat your listing with the respect and courtesy you would at your own home.
- **accommodates**: This allows you to select the maximum number of people that can comfortably fit in your place. It’s important to understand that capacity is not limited to bed space: you will have the opportunity to indicate the number of available beds in the subsequent steps (given you selected the “Entire home/apt” room type). For now, calculate how many people you can accommodate if each has his or her own bed, sofa bed, or inflatable mattress, provided that the sleeping arrangement is as comfortable as you would expect if you were the guest yourself. Finally, select the appropriate number from the drop-down list given.
- **bathrooms**: the number of bathrooms
- **bedrooms**: the number of bedrooms
- **beds**: the number of beds
- **bed_type**: the bed type
- **price**: the price
- **weekly_price**: the weekly price
- **monthly_price**: the monthly price
- **security_deposit**: the security deposit
- **cleaning_fee**the cleaning fee
- **guests_included**: the guests included
- **extra_people**: the price for each extra people
- **minimum_nights**; the minimum nights
- **maximum_nights**: the maximum nights
- **availability_30**: the availability in 30 days
- **availability_60**: the availability in 60 days
- **availability_90**: the availability in 90 days
- **availability_365**: the availability in 365 days
- **number_of_reviews**: the number of reviews
- **review_scores_rating**: the review scores rating
- **review_scores_accuracy**: the review scores accuracy
- **review_scores_cleanliness**: the review scores cleanliness
- **review_scores_checkin**: the review scores checkin
- **review_scores_communication**: the review scores communication
- **review_scores_location**: the review scores location
- **review_scores_value**: the review scores value
- **review_per_month**: the review per month
- **instant_bookable**: if is instant bookable
- **cancellation_policy**: the cancellation policy
- **require_guest_profile_picture**: if required guest profile picture
- **require_guest_phone_verification**: if require guest phone verification
- **calculated_host_listings_count**: the calculated host listings count
- **cultural_organizations**: the score of the district in relation the number of cultural organization between 1 (worst) and 5 (best). We have 5 districts, so they are ordered and the score was make in relation the order.
- **incidents**: the score of the district in relation the incidents between 1 (worst) and 5 (best). We have 5 districts, so they are ordered and the score was make in relation the order.
